<p>Osteoclasts are considered bone-dissolving cells. They are responsible for breaking down and resorbing bone tissue. Osteoclasts play a crucial role in bone remodeling and maintaining bone health. They are derived from monocytes and are multinucleated cells that secrete enzymes and acids to dissolve the mineralized matrix of bone. Their activity is regulated by various factors, such as hormones and cytokines. Osteoclasts are essential for the balance between bone resorption and formation, and any disruption in their function can lead to bone diseases like osteoporosis.</p>
